gene@netcom.com (gene m. stover) writes:

>Here's an example of a book cipher system:

>	cipher_char = (page, line, position)

>where the character at (page, line, position) in some book (the KEY)
>is the coresponding character of the plaintext. Note that each
>ciphertext "character" is a 3-tuple (which may or may not be expressed
>as such).

Usually we are talking about a book *code*, and the "3-tuple" indicates
a *word*. With characters, it's just a "simple" encryption with lots
of alternate cipher chars for a given plaintext char. It'd also be
a *bitch* to encrypt or decrypt a message unless the book is on disk!

